My fix in `ThreadCache.java` ensures that when a thread moves to a new revision, it unpins the old revision. 

One detail: `ThreadCache` is stored in a `ThreadLocal` in `ThreadBridge`. 
```java
final class ThreadBridge {
    private static final ThreadLocal<ThreadCache> ROUTES = ThreadLocal.withInitial(ThreadCache::new);
```
If multiple `TextDaemon` instances are created in the same process using the same threads (not the case here since `TextDaemon` creates its own pool), there could be issues. But here, each `TextDaemon` has its own `TimelineLedger` and its own `ExecutorService`. 

Wait! If the worker threads are reused across different `TextDaemon` instances (not happening here) or if the `ThreadLocal` persists... but the `ThreadLocal` is static in `ThreadBridge`. 

Actually, if I create `TextDaemon1`, it uses worker threads. These threads get a `ThreadCache` in their `ThreadLocal` map. When `TextDaemon1` is closed, the threads are shut down. 

If I then create `TextDaemon2`, it gets NEW threads. These new threads will have their own `ThreadLocal` maps.

So the static `ThreadLocal` is not a problem for thread reuse between daemons because the threads themselves are not reused.

However, there is one thing: `ThreadCache.cursorFor(TimelineLedger ledger)`.
